Drunk on corruption
My friend Boris was about to leave my house, drunk.
I therefore suggested that he not drive.
He asked me why.
"you've been drinking," I said to him, "aren't you afraid of the police?"
Boris replied to me: "No, I possess a document bearing the likeness of Benjamin Franklin, it always comes in handy."
He showed me his driver's license with the $100 bill slipped next to it.
Of course, I knew that the police took bribes, but I was worried that Boris might come across a police officer who was not corrupt.
"Impossible," declared Boris, "to get into the traffic police force, you have to buy your boss's silence."
If you don't take bribes, how can you buy your boss's silence?
Half of the drivers in Moscow use illegally purchased driver's licenses.
The fools who try to do things by the book drown in bureaucratic hassle.
By paying $100, you can drive around the city without brakes!
Corruption and embezzlement have always existed in Russia, before the October Revolution of Lenin and after.
But never at the levels seen today.
Everyone accepts bribes, everywhere and for everything.
The only ones who don't accept them are those to whom none are offered, according to Boris.
Corruption flourishes in most institutions, and the fight against corruption always ends in a catastrophe or an abandonment.
The police, prosecutors, customs officers, and even the Kremlin: no one, nowhere, is immune.
Recently, I was visiting a dacha village in one of the most beautiful suburbs of Moscow.
It was a luxurious place but similar to the gulag with its high-security fences and guards.
Looking at the pretentious houses decorated with such little taste, I wondered who owned them and heard myself answer that one of them belonged to a deputy mayor of Moscow, another to a famous singer, and another still to the son of a Moscow prosecutor.
But the most attractive property belonged to a modest tax service official.
Corruption now represents a greater threat to Russia than the Chechen war.
In fact, the Chechen war would not have lasted as long if it had not been waged by corrupt generals, officers, officials, and police officers who sell weapons and supplies to the rebels.
The Russian television recently showed a bus shuttling between Grozny and Moscow, the same bus that brought the 120 kilograms of explosives used in the Dubrovka theater siege, where so many victims perished during the operation to rescue the hostages.
A passenger on the bus covered the explosives with a cloth soaked in acid to prevent the customs dogs from detecting them.
A pointless precaution.
No one controls the buses today.
The driver, who didn't know what he was transporting, said he was stopped 50 times along the way, and always for the same reason.
A policeman would come to ask him, "Do you know the price?" and the driver would reply, "Of course, I know it," paying the bribe before leaving again.
Without a bribe, the bus would have been delayed for hours at each stop, amounting to entire days for the entire journey.
The war against Chechnya continues indefinitely not only because the Chechen rebels have allies in Al Qaïda and all of "the international terrorist network," but also because Russian corruption is their ally.
The police, the army, civilians who accept bribes, and thieves, who first tax Chechen civilians or simply steal their belongings, sell weapons and explosives to terrorists, provide maps indicating the locations of minefields, and supply rebels with fake documents.
In May of this year, during the Kaspiisk explosions, the terrorists used weapons purchased from Russian army officers.
The rebels have modern weapons.
Where do they come from?
In the mountains where the rebels hide, there are no gun shops.
But the 80,000 Russian soldiers fighting the rebels have their own stockpiles of ammunition, from which the weapons are stolen and sold.
And not only weapons: some young officers sell their own men into slavery.
Russian corruption has reached catastrophic levels, yet no campaign has been launched against this plague.
Punish corruption more severely?
This would only raise the price of corruption.
The harsher the punishment, the more one will have to pay to avoid it.
No official wants to fight corruption because they themselves are corrupt.
Thus, those referred to as "the simple people" consider this phenomenon with benevolence.
They say of their mayor, "Of course, he steals, but look at all he's done for the city!"
The ordinary people also dislike honest workers.
Why?
A train ticket costs 100 rubles, but by paying a small bribe, one can travel for 50 rubles.
The traveler and the ticket inspector both benefit from this system.
An honest old grandmother once told me that she had bought a ticket and tried to board the train.
The inspector had stopped her, telling her that passengers with a ticket were not allowed on the train!
For millions of Russians, corruption is a normal way of life.
If you don't want your son called up for military service, buy an army clerk and he will strike your son's name off the list, or bribe a doctor to declare him unfit for any military activity.
You can enter any faculty for a certain price, regardless of your references and diplomas.
You can drive drunk, speed, ignore red lights, as long as Ben Franklin is there to offer himself to the police.
Alexander Menchikov, the minister of Peter the Great, understood the impossibility of winning the battle against corruption.
When Tsar Peter, disgusted by the corruption in Russia, decided to hang his corrupt officials, Menchikov replied: "Your Majesty, you risk losing all your subjects."
In the centuries that have passed since, the situation has worsened.
Eliminating corruption could leave the state without citizens, but if we do not stop the spread of corruption, the citizens will soon be left without a state.
